initial statement:
 1152
Your Honor,

I stand before this court today to plead guilty for the offense I have committed. I, Robert Chapman, acknowledge that I was caught speeding in my brand-new car, and I take full responsibility for my actions.

I must admit that I allowed my curiosity to get the best of me, as I wanted to test the limits of my vehicle's capabilities. I understand now the danger I posed to those around me and the potential consequences that could have ensued. I deeply regret the risk I took and the impact it may have had on others.

Furthermore, I must acknowledge my failure to promptly respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). I apologize for my negligence in not regularly checking my mail, which resulted in my failure to address the situation in a timely manner. I assure you that had I been aware of the notice, I would have promptly taken the necessary actions to rectify the situation.

Your Honor, I am aware that I have previous penalty points on my license from three previous speeding incidents. However, aside from these driving offenses, I have a clean record. I would like to emphasize that my intention is not to offend or cause harm, but rather to express my remorse and commitment to learning from my mistakes.

In addition, I have been diagnosed with ADHD, which may have contributed to my impulsive behavior and lack of attention to important matters such as addressing the NIP. While this does not excuse my actions, it does provide some context for my behavior.

I have learned a valuable lesson from this experience, and I am determined to make positive changes in my life. I assure the court that I have taken steps to prevent the recurrence of such offenses. I have sought professional help and support to develop strategies to manage my impulsive tendencies and improve my attention to important matters.

Furthermore, I would like to express my willingness to make amends for the harm caused by my actions. I understand that this may include facing the consequences imposed by the court, as well as any additional measures deemed necessary. I am committed to learning from this experience and proving myself as a responsible member of society.

In conclusion, Your Honor, I plead guilty for my offense and accept the consequences of my actions. I ask for your leniency while considering the mitigating factors present in my case, including my lack of prior criminal record, my acknowledgment of the offense, my steps towards prevention, and the personal growth I have undergone as a result of this situation.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Sincerely,
Robert Chapman
