Your Honor,

I, Robert Chapman, am appearing before this honorable court today to plead guilty for the offense of speeding. I understand the seriousness of my actions and the potential harm I caused to others.

I deeply regret my decision to test the speed of my new car. I was carried away by curiosity and the excitement of owning a brand-new vehicle. However, I fully recognize that my actions were irresponsible and put the safety of others at risk, for which I am sincerely sorry.

I want to acknowledge that I failed to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). It is important to note that I have a habit of neglecting my mail, and unfortunately, this notice went unnoticed. I need to take responsibility for not being diligent in checking and attending to my mail. Had I been aware of the notice, I would have promptly addressed it.

While I have made mistakes in the past, including three previous incidents of speeding, I want the court to know that I do not have a record outside of these driving offenses. Additionally, it is important to mention that I have been diagnosed with ADHD, which may have contributed to my impulsive decision-making in this situation. However, I understand that this does not excuse my behavior and that I need to take appropriate measures to manage my condition better.

I wholeheartedly acknowledge my guilt and am prepared to face the consequences of my actions. I respectfully request Your Honor to consider the unique circumstances surrounding my case. This experience has been a valuable lesson for me, and I am committed to making better choices and following all traffic laws in the future.

I thank you for your understanding and for granting me the opportunity to express my remorse. I appreciate the time and consideration you have given to my case.

