I, Robert Chapman, stand before this honorable court to express my sincerest apologies and to plead guilty for the offense of speeding. I am fully aware of the gravity of my actions and the potential harm I imposed on others.

The impulsive decision to test the limits of my new car was a grave mistake that I deeply regret. While the exhilaration of owning a brand-new vehicle caused me to act recklessly, I hold myself accountable for the irresponsible behavior that endangered the safety of those around me.

I humbly acknowledge that I neglected to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP) that was sent to me. Admittedly, I have not been diligent in attending to my mail, and unfortunately, the NIP went unnoticed. I fully acknowledge my responsibility in failing to keep abreast of important correspondence. Had I known about the notice, I would have promptly and appropriately addressed it.

I want to emphasize that besides these driving offenses, I do not have a record of any other infractions. However, I do have ADHD, which may have contributed to my impulsive decision-making in this particular instance. While this does not excuse my behavior, it provides valuable context as I strive to manage my condition better.

By pleading guilty, I aim to show my unwavering acceptance of responsibility and remorse for my actions. I understand that my plea helps expedite the legal process and allows this honorable court to allocate its valuable time and resources elsewhere. I am fully prepared to face the consequences of my actions and make amends for the hazards I posed on the road.

I beseech Your Honor to consider the unique circumstances surrounding my case. This experience has served as a profound lesson for me, reinforcing the importance of making responsible choices and adhering to all traffic laws. I assure you that I am genuinely committed to personal growth and ensuring that such misconduct is never repeated.

I extend my gratitude for allowing me the opportunity to express my remorse and take full accountability for my actions. Your understanding and consideration are humbly appreciated.

Respectfully,
Robert Chapman
